{"title":"Positive Indexing","markdown":{"headingText":"Positive Indexing","headingAttr":{"id":"sec-positive-indexing","classes":[],"keyvalue":[]},"containsRefs":false,"markdown":"\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-problem}\n**The Problem**\n\nYour supervisor asks: \"What was the age of the very first participant enrolled? And can you show me the ages of the first ten participants, so I can spot-check the data entry?\" You have a 100-value `age` vector, but you've only ever printed the *whole* thing at once — you don't yet know how to pull out just one value, or just a few, from a specific position.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mission}\n**Your Mission**\n\nExtract specific elements from a vector by their position, using square brackets.\n:::\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-think}\n**Think Before Coding**\n\n- If someone asked you for \"the 3rd item on this list,\" how would you count to find it — starting from 0 or from 1?\n- What if you wanted several positions at once, like the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd — could you reuse something you learned two pages ago (sequences) to describe \"1 through 10\"?\n:::\n\n## The R Concept\n\n**Indexing** means extracting one or more elements from a vector using square brackets, `[ ]`, containing the position(s) you want:\n\n```r\nx[position]\n```\n\nCritically, **R is 1-indexed** — the first element is at position `1`, not `0` (unlike some other programming languages you may encounter later, such as Python). This is one of the most important structural facts to internalize early.\n\n```r\nages <- c(46, 53, 59, 49, 61)\nages[1]      # the FIRST element - not the second\nages[3]      # the third element\nages[1:3]    # the first three elements, using the sequence range from the last page\n```\n\nYou can also pass a vector of specific, non-consecutive positions: `ages[c(1, 3, 5)]` returns the 1st, 3rd, and 5th elements.\n\n## Demonstration\n\n```r\nages <- c(46, 53, 59, 49, 61, 18, 62, 68, 33, 36)\n\nages[1]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 46\n```\n\n```r\nages[1:10]\n```\n\n```\n [1] 46 53 59 49 61 18 62 68 33 36\n```\n\n```r\nages[c(2, 5, 9)]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 53 61 33\n```\n\n## Explore\n\nTry `ages[11]` — one position past the end of a 10-element vector. What does R return, and why do you think it doesn't produce an error? Then try `ages[0]` — an unusual edge case worth seeing once.\n\n## Solve the Problem\n\n```r\nparticipants <- read.csv(\"data/participants.csv\")\n\n# Age of the very first participant enrolled\nparticipants$age[1]\n```\n\n```\n[1] 46\n```\n\n```r\n# Ages of the first ten participants\nparticipants$age[1:10]\n```\n\n```\n [1] 46 53 59 49 61 18 62 68 33 36\n```\n\n## Interpret the Result\n\nThe first participant enrolled was 46 years old, and the first ten participants ranged across ages including 18, 33, and 68 — exactly the kind of quick spot-check your supervisor asked for, pulled directly from specific positions in the `age` column without scrolling through the entire 100-row dataset.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-mistake}\n**Common Mistakes**\n\n- **Assuming R is 0-indexed.** `ages[0]` does not return the first element — it returns an empty vector of length zero, since position `0` doesn't correspond to any real element in R's 1-indexed system.\n- **Using `()` instead of `[]`.** `ages(1)` is not valid indexing syntax — parentheses are for function calls, not for extracting elements from a vector.\n- **Indexing past the end silently.** `ages[11]` on a 10-element vector doesn't error — it returns `NA`, since R interprets it as \"the value at a position that doesn't exist.\" This can silently introduce missing values into further calculations if you're not paying attention.\n:::\n\n## Practice Problem\n\nUsing `participants$bmi`, extract the BMI of the 15th participant, and separately, the BMIs of the first 5 participants.\n\n## Challenge Problem\n\nExtract the ages of the 1st, 50th, and 100th participants in a single line of code (hint: you'll need `c()` inside the square brackets). Then explain, in one sentence, why `participants$age[1, 50, 100]` (with commas but no `c()`) would not work the way you might expect.\n\n## Key Takeaways\n\n- Square brackets `[ ]` extract elements from a vector by position; R is 1-indexed, so the first element is at position `1`.\n- A range (`1:10`) or an arbitrary set of positions (`c(2, 5, 9)`) can both be used inside `[ ]`.\n- Indexing past the end of a vector doesn't error — it silently returns `NA`, which is worth watching for.\n\n::: {.pbl-box .pbl-check}\n**Knowledge Check**\n\n1. **Multiple choice.** What does `x[1]` return for `x <- c(10, 20, 30)`?\n   a) `20`\n   b) `10`\n   c) An error, since indexing starts at 0\n   d) The entire vector\n\n2. **True or false.** R is 0-indexed, like Python.\n\n3. **Predict the output.**\n   ```r\n   x <- c(10, 20, 30, 40)\n   x[c(1, 4)]\n   ```\n\n4. **Find the error.**\n   ```r\n   ages(3)\n   ```\n\n<details class=\"pbl-answer\">\n<summary>Show answers</summary>\n\n1. **b)** `10` — the first element, since R is 1-indexed.\n2. **False.** R is 1-indexed; the first element is at position 1, not 0.\n3. `[1] 10 40`\n4. Parentheses are used for function calls, not indexing. It should be `ages[3]`.\n\n</details>\n:::\n","srcMarkdownNoYaml":""},"formats":{"html":{"identifier":{"display-name":"HTML","target-format":"html","base-format":"html"},"execute":{"fig-width":7,"fig-height":5,"fig-format":"retina","fig-dpi":96,"df-print":"default","error":false,"eval":true,"cache":null,"freeze":"auto","echo":true,"output":true,"warning":false,"include":true,"keep-md":false,"keep-ipynb":false,"ipynb":null,"enabled":null,"daemon":null,"daemon-restart":false,"debug":false,"ipynb-filters":[],"ipynb-shell-interactivity":null,"plotly-connected":true,"message":false,"engine":"markdown"},"render":{"keep-tex":false,"keep-typ":false,"keep-source":false,"keep-hidden":false,"prefer-html":false,"output-divs":true,"output-ext":"html","fig-align":"default","fig-pos":null,"fig-env":null,"code-fold":false,"code-overflow":"scroll","code-link":true